dataqual.logic: This parcel layer contains discrete, non-overlapping polygons for each property. Adjacent polygons with common ownership and a single tax record have been retained in the "OthLeg" layer that accompanies this TaxPar layer, and dissolved into single parcels in this TaxPar layer. Some non-adjacent parcels may be represented by multi-part polygons where they share common ownership and a single tax record. Public right of ways exist as polygons, not null space. Linework associated with private ROWs are retained in the "OthLeg" layer. Water polygons also representing parcel boundaries have been retained in this TaxPar layer. Additional water features that are not considered parcel boundaries may have been placed in the "Misc" layer that accompanies this TaxPar layer. Easements and other similar non-fee taxable boundaries exist in the 'OthLeg" layer, not the TaxPar layer.

srcinfo.srccitea: Cape Cod Commission parcel layer and James W. Sewall hand drawn paper book, along with individual subdivision and surveyor plans
srcinfo.srccontr: Parcel layer originally digitized by Cape Cod Commission, but maintained in paper maps by the James W. Sewall Company for the Town until Fiscal Year 2005. Standard planimetrics were developed under a data sharing agreement with NStar in 2003. Additional data sets, topography, and orthophotos were developed from the same 2003 photos by James W. Sewall Company. EarthTech updated the Cape Cod Commission earlier parcel polygon layer that was available on MassGIS at that time to the 2003 photos and Fiscal Year 2006. All parcels align to 100 scale accuracy of the 2003 planimetrics. Continuing maintenance from fiscal year 2008 to current has been done by Geo-GIS under contract to the Assessing Department directly.

procstep.procdesc: The Sandwich parcel polygon layer was already corrected to 100 scale accuracy and FY'11 status. The conformance project first invovled generating centroids for all the polygons to create the LOC_ID. The CAMA data was exported from the Assessor's system, which is not a standard CAMA system provided by Data National, only a few Towns in Massachusetts use this sytem. The data was adjusted to the Level III conformance headings and checked for accuracy. Inconsistencies were corrected and adjusted to the best of our ability in keeping with as standardized as an output as possible for future updates. The town boundary was checked and adjustments were made to align with the Town_Survey layer from MassGIS. Additional line corrections were made to the polygon layer to follow ROW, and clean up property lines. The CAMA match rates were generated and additional questions were referred back to the Town of Sandwich Assessing Department. Two site visits were made in addition to multiple phone and email communication over the course of March to June 2011 to meet Level III conformance requirements.

overview.dsoverv: Tax parcel polygons for Sandiwch, MA. This data set contains polygons which delineate property ownership in the town of Sandiwch, according to the assessor's tax maps as of March 2011. It is formatted in compliance with the MassGIS Standard for Digital Parcel Files, Version 2.0. This data set is considered to be MassGIS Level III-compliant and is derived from an upgrade of the previous Level II-compliant version of this same data set.

onLineSrc.orDesc: Assessor's parcel data for town of Sanwich, MA. Developed from existing digital data.
Click on the "Download this layer" link to access all digital parcels.

M261TaxPar represents a version of digital municipal parcels for the community of <Town Name> that is considered ‘level 3’ compliant per the specifications outlined in the MassGIS Standard for Digital Parcel Files. Its features can be linked in a GIS or database environment to a set of standardized assessing attributes in the table M261Assess by using the unique identifying values in the LOC_ID field. This data is also intended to be used in conjunction with associated (and optional) features in the ancillary data layers M261OthLeg and M261Misc. As one of the data sets in the Massachusetts’ Spatial Data Infrastructure, this data enters the public domain as a valuable resource for mapping, planning, and analysis at all levels of government as well as the private sector.
